'''Sandra Deal''' (née '''Emilie Sandra Dunagan''';<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L-_zoKQ-mvQC |title=Official Congressional Directory|publisher=Government Printing Office|page=75}}</ref> born in [[Gainesville, Georgia]]) is an American education activist and former public school language arts teacher. As the wife of Georgia state's current governor, [[Nathan Deal]], she has been the [[First Lady]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] since 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.macon.com/news/local/article97022012.html|title=Georgia's first lady talks school bus safety|last=Woolen|first=Angela|website=[[The Telegraph (Macon)|The Telegraph]]|publication-date=2016-08-21}}</ref>
==Education== The daughter of educators, Emilie Sandra Dunagan grew up in [[Gainesville, Georgia]]. She graduated from [[Georgia College & State University]].<ref name=nge>{{Cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/government-politics/nathan-deal-b-1942 |title=Nathan Deal (b. 1942) |last=McKee |first=Sarah |website=[[New Georgia Encyclopedia]] |publication-date=2011-10-10}}</ref> ==Career== [[File:Milledgeville Grand Opening (32512930632).jpg|thumb|First Lady Deal at the Milledgeville Grand Opening]] Before becoming the first lady of Georgia, Dunagan taught language arts at public schools for over 15 years, and retired as a sixth-grade middle-school teacher in [[Hall County, Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.georgia.gov/biography-1|title=First Lady Biography|website=[[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] official government website}}</ref> As Georgia's first lady, she is known for advocating for literacy and education throughout the state,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdjonline.com/news/georgia-first-lady-shares-love-of-reading/article_47f2311c-b6a2-11e6-8a3b-cb2037464326.html|title=Georgiafirst lady shares love of reading|last=McGowan|first=Mary Kate|website=[[Marietta Daily Journal]]|publication-date=2016-11-29}}</ref> for which the [[Georgia Association of Broadcasters]] awarded her their 2016 "Georgian of the Year" award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gab.org/2016-georgian-of-the-year|title=First Lady Sandra Deal Named 2016 Georgian of the Year|last=Story|first=Luke |website=[[Georgia Association of Broadcasters]]|publication-date=2016-06-09}}</ref>
In 2015, her book ''Memories of the Mansion: The Story of Georgia’s Governor’s Mansion'' was published.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/morning_call/2015/09/georgia-first-lady-sandra-deal-releases-book.html|title=Georgia First Lady Sandra Deal releases book|last=Caldwell|first=Carla|website=[[Atlanta Business Chronicle]]|publication-date=2015-09-30}}</ref>
In 2016, she served as the keynote speaker at [[Georgia Gwinnett College]]'s summer commencement.<ref>{{Cite press release|title=First Lady Sandra Deal to speak at GGC summer commencement|date=2016-07-22|publisher=[[Georgia Gwinnett College]]|url=http://www.ggc.edu/about-ggc/news/News/first-lady-sandra-deal-to-speak-at-ggc-summer-commencement}}</ref>
==Personal life== Dunagan married Deal in 1966.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Memories of the Mansion: The Story of Georgia’s Governor’s Mansion|publisher=[[University of Georgia Press]]|year=2015|page=168}}</ref> She and Deal have four children: Jason, Mary Emily, Carrie, and Katie.<ref name=nge/>
Sandra Deal was diagnosed with [[breast cancer]] in January 2018.<ref>[https://www.gainesvilletimes.com/news/georgia-first-lady-sandra-deal-diagnosed-breast-cancer-has-tumor-removed Georgia first lady Sandra Deal diagnosed with breast cancer, has tumor removed], gainesvilletimes.com; accessed January 29, 2018.</ref>
