[[File:SAFE logo registered.jpg|thumb]] The '''Society of Aviation and Flight Educators''' ('''SAFE''') is a professional organization open to all [[aviation]] educators, including [[flight instructor]]s, [[Ground Instructor|ground instructors]], academicians, and others who have an interest in aviation education. Founded in [[Connecticut]] in early 2009, SAFE "facilitates the professional development of aviation educators [and] seeks to create a safer aviation environment through enhanced education."<ref name="vms">{{cite web|url=http://www.safepilots.org/governance/vision-mission-statements/|title=Vision and Mission Statements|publisher=Society of Aviation and Flight Educators|accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref> SAFE is governed by a Board of Directors composed of nine members, all of whom are elected by the SAFE membership in a rotating three year cycle.
SAFE introduced scenario-based training into aviation in 2009 with the creation of the '''[https://www.safepilots.org/programs/pilot-proficiency-project%e2%84%a2/ Pilot Proficiency Program]'''. Using the (then brand new) '''[https://simulators.redbirdflight.com/about Redbird Flight Simulator]''', this program challenged pilots with adventurous skill and risk-management story lines. This program expanded to become the popular (EAA) '''[http://eaapilotproficiency.com/ Pilot Proficiency Center]''' that is a highlight of '''[[EAA AirVenture Oshkosh|AirVenture]]''' every year. [[File:SAFE-PilotTrainingReformSymposium2011.png|thumb|SAFE 2011 Pilot Training Reform Symposium]] In 2011 SAFE transformed the flight training system in the United States with the '''[http://www.pilottrainingreform.org/ Pilot Training Reform Symposium]'''. This meeting attracted users, partners and major FAA officials including '''[http://www.pilottrainingreform.org/the-faa-administrators-speech/ FAA Administrator Randy Babbitt]''' and led to extensive changes in FAA guidance and policy. One significant outcome of this symposium was the introduction of the '''[https://www.faa.gov/training_testing/testing/acs/ Airman Testing Standards]''' (ACS) in June 2016. This revolutionary change introduced the third pillar of flight safety, risk management, into the previous skill and knowledge test requirements of the '''[[Practical Test Standards]]''' (PTS). The ACS also integrated the knowledge and flight testing components into a more efficient and valid evaluation formatted into a real-life scenario structure.
SAFE was also revolutionary in developing their own '''[https://www.safepilots.org/programs/cfi-liability-insurance/ aviation educator insurance program]''' to protect their members. This program, launched in collaboration with '''STARR insurance''', provides comprehensive insurance specifically for flight instructors, including all categories and class aircraft they are rated to fly. Significant discounts are available to '''[http://www.masterinstructors.org/ Master Flight Instructors]''' and '''[[FAA WINGS|FAA Wings]]''' participants to incentivize professional development and the pursuit of excellence.
SAFE has signed letters of understanding with a number of organizations, including [[Cessna Aircraft Company]]<ref name="eva222">{{cite news|url=http://www.evaint.com/daily-news/5362/Cessna-becomes-exclusive-sponsor-of-SAFEs-website.aspx|title=Cessna becomes exclusive sponsor of SAFE's website|date=Feb 22, 2010|publisher=EVA International|accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref> and the [[FAA]] Safety Team.<ref>[http://www.safepilots.org/documents/FAASTeam_SAFE_LOU_27Feb09.pdf] Letter of Understanding between SAFE and FAASTeam</ref> SAFE is also a sponsor of the General Aviation Awards Program.<ref name="gaa">{{cite web|url=http://www.generalaviationawards.org/page/ga-awards-program-sponsors|title=GA Awards Program Sponsors|publisher=General Aviation Awards|accessdate=8 February 2011}}</ref> The organization is proactive on issues that affect aviation educators<ref name="ann1">{{cite news|url=http://www.aero-news.net/news/genav.cfm?ContentBlockID=3EBD0CB1-33A2-4F63-AA2B-1CA96F4D39C2&Dynamic=1|title=SAFE Opposes California Assembly Bill 48|date=June 7, 2010|work=Aero-News.Net|publisher=Aero-News Network, Inc.|accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref><ref name="ann2">{{cite news|url=http://www.aero-news.net/news/genav.cfm?ContentBlockID=957C7C51-A8C0-4339-8582-0352A0792D0A&Dynamic=1|title=SAFE Responds to Photo ID NPRM| date=January 18, 2011|work=Aero-News.Net|publisher=Aero-News Network, Inc.|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> and has partnered with others to develop a mentoring program for aviation educators.<ref name="gan1">{{cite news|url=http://www.generalaviationnews.com/2010/04/13/safe-launches-mentoring-program/|title=SAFE launches mentoring program|date=April 13, 2010|work=GeneralAviationNews.com|publisher=General Aviation News|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> In July 2010, SAFE launched a flight instructor liability insurance program<ref name="gan2">{{cite news|url=http://www.generalaviationnews.com/2010/07/22/new-cfi-insurance-program-from-safe/|title=New CFI insurance program from SAFE |date=July 22, 2010|work=GeneralAviationNews.com|publisher=General Aviation News|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> developed for its member-instructors. In November 2010, SAFE announced plans to chair the GA Pilot Training Reform Symposium.<ref name="gan3">{{cite news|url=http://www.generalaviationnews.com/2010/11/15/pilot-training-reform-symposium-slated/|title=Pilot Training Reform Symposium slated |date=November 15, 2010|work=GeneralAviationNews.com|publisher=General Aviation News|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> {{clear}}
